{{US-business-bio-stub}}

[[Image:Leaping salmon at Chester Business Park - Sculpture by Laurence Broderick.jpg|thumb|alt=Leaping Salmon sculpture at Chester Business Park by Laurence Broderick|Leaping Salmon at Chester Business Park, by sculptor [[Laurence Broderick]]]]
'''Chester Business Park''' is located to the south of the city of [[Chester]], [[Cheshire]], England and is sited to the east of Wrexham Road ([[A483 road|A483]]) and to the north of the Chester southerly bypass ([[A55 road|A55]]).

The park opened in 1988<ref name=vch>{{Citation | last = Thacker| first = A. T.| author-link = | last2 = Lewis | first2 = C. P. (eds.)| author2-link = | publication-date = | date = | year = 2003| title = Twentieth century Chester 1914-2000: The economy, 1974-2000| edition = | volume = 5, Part 1| series = A History of the County of Chester: The City of Chester: General History and Topography | publication-place = | place = | publisher = | pages = 266–269| page = | id = | isbn = | doi = | oclc = | url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=19234&strquery=farm | accessdate = 13 January 2010}}</ref> and occupies an area of {{convert|175|acre|km2}}.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.chesterbusinesspark.com/| title = Chester Business Park| accessdate = 13 January 2010| publisher =Chester Business Park Management Company}}</ref> At the centre of the site is the former [[Wrexham Road Farm, Eccleston|Wrexham Road Farm]], a [[model farm]] designed by [[John Douglas (architect)|John Douglas]] for the [[Hugh Grosvenor, 1st Duke of Westminster|1st Duke of Westminster]] and built in 1877–84; otherwise it was a [[Greenfield land|greenfield site]]. The farmhouse and outbuildings of the farm were converted into offices, and a number of businesses built premises in modern architectural styles. One of the first major businesses to occupy a new building was [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell Chemicals U.K.]], and other businesses included [[Marks & Spencer|Marks & Spencer Financial Services]], [[MBNA|MBNA International Bank]], [[Bristol-Myers Squibb]], and [[Trinity Mirror|Trinity International]].<ref name=vch/>

A Leaping Salmon bronze sculpture by [[Laurence Broderick]] is displayed at the Chester Business Park.

