'''Compliance Ireland''' was formally established in January 2004, but informally commenced in mid-2003.  It is a [[private company]], but uniquely it writes on, and contributes to, numerous [[debate]]s in [[Ireland]] about [[corporate governance]] and [[compliance (regulation)|compliance]] on an independent basis.  Compliance Ireland is frequently quoted in [[newspaper]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepost.ie/story/eygbaumhey/ |title=The Sunday Business Post |publisher=Thepost.ie |date= |accessdate=2014-02-05}} {{Dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.tribune.ie/article/2009/oct/25/bermudan-must-make-bad-banking-disappear/?q=peter%20oakes ]{{dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref> government reports,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhsbsa.nhs.uk/CounterFraud/Documents/International_fraud_and_corruption_report.pdf |title=The International Fraud and Corruption Report |format=PDF |date=July 2006 |accessdate=2014-02-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020021109/http://www.nhsbsa.nhs.uk/CounterFraud/Documents/International_fraud_and_corruption_report.pdf |archivedate=2013-10-20 |df= }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=February 2014}} television,<ref>{{cite web|first=Aoife |last=Kavanagh |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0224/primetime.html |title=Prime Time GAA: Cork Hurling Crisis |publisher=RTÉ Sport |date=2009-02-24 |accessdate=2014-02-05}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=February 2014}} radio<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0302/morningireland.html |title=RTÉ News: Morning Ireland |publisher=RTÉ.ie |date= |accessdate=2014-02-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221142307/http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0302/morningireland.html |archivedate=2014-02-21 |df= }}</ref> and [[Wikipedia]].<ref>[[Financial Regulator]]</ref>

Compliance Ireland has been both a measured critic and supporter of the [[Financial Regulator]] and [[Central Bank of Ireland|Central Bank]] since the two entities were loosely joined in 2003 following a wide sweeping regulatory review commenced by [[Michael McDowell (politician)|Michael McDowell]] (former T.D, Minister for Justice and [[Tánaiste]]) in the late 1990s and published in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finance.gov.ie/viewdoc.asp?DocID=1332 |title=Page Redirection |publisher=Finance.gov.ie |date= |accessdate=2014-02-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220095847/http://www.finance.gov.ie/viewdoc.asp?DocID=1332 |archivedate=February 20, 2012 }}</ref>  In early 2009 the Irish Prime Minister or [[Taoiseach]], [[Brian Cowen]], announced the creation of a new unitary [[central bank]] and [[financial services]] regulator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0228/fiannafail.html |title=New Central Banking Commission announced |publisher=[[RTÉ News]] |date=2009-03-02 |accessdate=2014-02-05}}</ref>  The proposed new regulator has been referred to by various names since it was announced.  It is expected to be known as the Central Bank of Ireland Commission (CBIC) or similar. The CIBC will replace the Central Bank and Financial Services Authority of Ireland created in 2003, although it did not receive its enforcement powers until 2004.  The Minister for Finance, [[Brian Lenihan Jnr|Brian Lenihan]], signaled that he would publish a Bill by the end of 2009. As of 31 December 2009 a Bill has yet to be published.

Notwithstanding a lack of a heads of Bill, the Minister has been busy appointing a new Governor ([[Patrick Honohan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finance.gov.ie/viewdoc.asp?DocID=5922&CatID=1&StartDate=1+January+2009&m= |title=Page Redirection |publisher=Finance.gov.ie |date= |accessdate=2014-02-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220095947/http://www.finance.gov.ie/viewdoc.asp?DocID=5922&CatID=1&StartDate=1%2BJanuary%2B2009&m= |archivedate=February 20, 2012 |df= }}</ref> and Head of Financial Regulation ([[Matthew Elderfield]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finance.gov.ie/viewdoc.asp?DocID=6021&CatID=1&StartDate=1+January+2009&m= |title=Page Redirection |publisher=Finance.gov.ie |date= |accessdate=2014-02-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220095954/http://www.finance.gov.ie/viewdoc.asp?DocID=6021&CatID=1&StartDate=1%2BJanuary%2B2009&m= |archivedate=February 20, 2012 |df= }}</ref> to spearhead central bank and financial services [[regulatory reform]] in Ireland. Governor Honohan commenced his position in October 2009 (taking over from Juhn Hurley) and Mr Elderfield will join the CBIC in early January 2010.  A number of significant and senior roles reporting into Mr Elderfield were advertised on 18 December 2009, including three Assistant Director-General roles (Enforcement, Policy & Risk and Markets Supervision)<ref>{{cite web|first=Thomas |last=Molloy |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/outsiders-to-get-key-regulatory-positions-1971223.html |title=Outsiders to get key regulatory positions |publisher=[[Irish Independent]] |date=2009-12-11 |accessdate=2014-02-05}}</ref> and the Registrar of Credit Unions.

